detail.content: JAMES DEAN AMERICA: Tisch School of the Arts at NYU                           Skip to content        Rita and Burton Goldberg Department of Dramatic Writing About the Program/Admissions Admissions Student Life Course Offerings News & Events Work of Writing Students Screenplay Showcase Fellowships/Contests Script Bank Sloan Winners Admin & Faculty Alumni Internships Contact  home > Dramatic Writing        JAMES DEAN AMERICA  Written by Joseph Mango Genre: Comedy-Drama Logline: When a wide-eyed producer's assistant at Warner Bros. stumbles upon a gem of a script that was to star James Dean before he died, he tracks down the cantankerous writer who refuses to release the script without the blessing of James Dean whom he swears is still alive. Bio: Joseph earned his MFA in May 2014 where he received the 2014 Dramatic Writing Chair's Award. He was born and raised in Youngstown, Ohio, the same town where the Warner brothers started their leap into the motion picture industry. As a film enthusiast, Joseph found writing/directing idols in Frank Capra, Billy Wilder, Chris Columbus, and Cameron Crowe. After earning his B.A. from the University of Southern California, Joseph worked as a production assistant and video playback production coordinator for feature films and television shows. He went on to work as an administrative specialist at a UCLA mental health research center where he co-wrote and co-produced a short film about depression that was recently accepted into publication. The stage version of James Dean America was selected for the 2013 NYU Festival of New Works and also received a nomination for the 2013 MFA Playwrights Workshop at the Kennedy Center. E-mail:  mango.joseph@gmail.com Website: www.writtenbyjoe.wordpress.com Twitter: @ joseph_domenick           Undergraduate Admissions Graduate Admissions Academic Services Student Life Financial Aid and Scholarships Career Development Counseling Services International Students Incoming Students Graduation Forms What is Special Programs? JAMES DEAN AMERICA: Tisch School of the Arts at NYU                           Skip to content        Rita and Burton Goldberg Department of Dramatic Writing About the Program/Admissions Admissions Student Life Course Offerings News & Events Work of Writing Students Screenplay Showcase Fellowships/Contests Script Bank Sloan Winners Admin & Faculty Alumni Internships Contact  home > Dramatic Writing        JAMES DEAN AMERICA  Written by Joseph Mango Genre: Comedy-Drama Logline: When a wide-eyed producer's assistant at Warner Bros. stumbles upon a gem of a script that was to star James Dean before he died, he tracks down the cantankerous writer who refuses to release the script without the blessing of James Dean whom he swears is still alive. Bio: Joseph earned his MFA in May 2014 where he received the 2014 Dramatic Writing Chair's Award. He was born and raised in Youngstown, Ohio, the same town where the Warner brothers started their leap into the motion picture industry. As a film enthusiast, Joseph found writing/directing idols in Frank Capra, Billy Wilder, Chris Columbus, and Cameron Crowe. After earning his B.A. from the University of Southern California, Joseph worked as a production assistant and video playback production coordinator for feature films and television shows. He went on to work as an administrative specialist at a UCLA mental health research center where he co-wrote and co-produced a short film about depression that was recently accepted into publication. The stage version of James Dean America was selected for the 2013 NYU Festival of New Works and also received a nomination for the 2013 MFA Playwrights Workshop at the Kennedy Center. Zagarrio, Vito               Dissertation Site         Cinema Studies    Home > PhD Graduates > Zagarrio, Vito           Alumni        PhD Graduates     MA Graduates     BA/BFA Graduates     MIAP Graduates         Search                    Author: Zagarrio, Vito Year: 1995    Dissertation Title:    Frank Capra malgre lui: a Filmmaker and the Contradictions of American Society 1922-34       Abstract:    The dissertation analyzes the film made by the director Frank Capra between 1928 and 1934. The work shows how Capra can be read in terms of his relationship to social history, and that he can even be turned into a case study, on the basis of which one may suggest a new kind of historical methodology.    The goal of the research is to cast Capra in a new light, pointing out the sense of abyss coexistent with his fairy-tale optimism, and the pessimism hidden behind his comedies. The director's work is viewed as a record of American social conflicts, of collective and personal depressions, and of the contradictions inherent in the spirit of capitalism they stereotypically express.    Capra has always been identified as a populist, demagogic, conservative filmmaker: the taste of "Capracorn," and the message that happiness comes from little people and little things, have defined--but also confined--him in terms of a certain vision of the post-Depression era, and his films have been classified as escapist fantasies of goodwill, portraying a sentimental view of American life.    On the contrary, analyzing certain sequences, and rereading certain frames of his films, the dissertation reveals symptoms of pathology, malaise, and madness of the American society. There is a conflicting image of the American imaginary, which Capra offers, perhaps malgre lui, in spite of himself. One can draw from his films the tragic landscape of the United States and a pessimistic vision of life that has its roots in immigration, poverty, class struggle, and the contradictions of the American Dream.    In fact, the dissertation analyzes certain indicative themes: the "unhappy ending", the obsession with suicide, the coming catastrophe, the family conflicts, the social conflicts, the crises of the system, and some symbolic "off-key" frames.
